08027nam a22008655i 9783110518269DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20182018pl     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105182697 a10.1515/97831105182692doi  a(DE-B1597)473442  a(OCoLC)1037979326  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aplcPL 4aP 7aLAN0090002bisacsh1 aCHUA Siew Kheng, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUn(intended) Language Planning in a Globalising World: Multiple Levels of Players at Work /cCatherine CHUA Siew Kheng. 1aWarsaw ;aBerlin : bDe Gruyter Open Poland, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Introduction. Issues in language planning and policy: From global to local -- t2 Is English global? -- t3 The language planning and policy for the European Union and its failures -- t4 Macro policies and meso language planning: The case of supranational policies in Europe -- t5 Inequalities of multilingualism: Outsourcing, neoliberalism and languages-in-education -- t6 Foreign language learning policy in the United Arab Emirates: Local and global agents of change -- t7 National security in language-in-education policy -- t8 A tale of two cities: Religion and language policy in Malaysia and Singapore -- t9 Language policy in business and industry: Between local and global developments -- t10 Translation in journalism: Local practices in multilingual newsflows -- t11 Chasing a phantom: Afrikaans in higher education in the globalisation era -- t12 Local challenges to global needs in English language education in Vietnam: The perspective of language policy and planning -- t13 English-medium instruction and teacher agency in higher education: A case study -- t14 English language education planning for Chinese schools - Multi-level actors at work -- t15 Translation of language policy from pre-school to primary school in Singapore: Multiplayers at work -- t16 Planning uses of Peace Linguistics in second language education -- t17 Language policy: From planning to management -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis first book provides a comprehensive overview of the different levels of players who have been involved in both intended and unintended language planning and policy, and shows how they have impacted multilingual language use. Specifically, it looks at the roles of different 'glo-national' (global national) players in directing the choices of language use in various parts of the world. Drawing on topics from numerous countries i.e., Basque country, Brazil, China, Europe, France, Germany, Japan, Malaysia, North Korea, Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Africa, Turkey, Vietnam, United Arab Emirates and the United States of America, this book showcases the complexity of language planning. The book not only provides examples to illustrate how globalisation has led to an increase in demand in learning English in many countries, it brings in other examples to demonstrate how globalisation has also promoted language diversity in other countries as well. Using the four stages of language planning framework - Supra Macro, Macro, Micro and Infra Micro levels of language planning, the book discusses the tension that surrounds the global, national and local demands on language choice, and presents the possible outcomes of the various intended and unintended policies, and strategies adopted by the different players found in these four stages of planning. The aim of the book is to highlight the importance of aligning the supra and macro levels of planning with the micro and infra macro levels of planning in any language planning in order to obtain positive outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individua